Dataset & Problem Framing 
Dataset: Used Car Listings Dataset — 24,988 records of vehicle listings spanning model years 2001 through 2026, covering a wide range of brands, body types, and fuel types. This dataset was sourced independently from Eric Toan, who web scraped this dataset, which contains 68 total columns, including performance specs, dimensions, and feature availability flags
Features:
Brand — Vehicle manufacturer (categorical).
Model Year — The year that vehicle was manufactured (continuous, Integer).
HP — Horsepower of the engine (continuous)
Fuel Type — Type of fuel the vehicle uses, ex: Gas, Electric, Diesel (categorical).
Target: 
Price — Listed sale price in USD (continuous, regression target).
Price range after cleaning: 3,000 – $200,000 USD.
Final dataset shape after preprocessing: 23,493 rows × 68 columns
Research Question: To what extent can machine learning models use vehicle attributes (horsepower, model year, fuel type, brand) to accurately predict used car prices?
Side Questions: 
1.	How does horsepower affect price?
2.	How much does model year affect price?
3.	How does brand affect price?
4.	How does fuel type affect price?
5.	What is the most important feature for predicting price?
Relevance: New cars are getting more and more expensive, and with so many people flocking to the used car market, a data‑driven model that can estimate a fair price based on important vehicle attributes can help consumers make more informed decisions when purchasing used cars.


Data Preprocessing & Assumptions
1.	Column Standardization: All columns were stripped of whitespace, lowercased, and special characters were replaced with underscores to help with consistency throughout the pipeline.

2.	Type Conversion: the columns price, model_year, and hp were converted to numeric types to handle any mixed‑type entries, coercing invalid values to NaN.

3.	Missing Value Handling: Rows missing any of the four core features were dropped using dropNA, ensuring that no imputed values distorted the key predictors.


4.	Outlier Filtering: Rows with a listed price below 3,000 USD or above 200,000 USD were removed to eliminate likely data entry errors and extreme outliers that heavily skewed the data.

5.	Feature Selection: Under the name main_features, the four core predictors — brand, model_year, hp, and fuel_type — were isolated from the full 68‑column dataset along with the target price.

6.	Side questions: Under the names df_HP, df_year, df_brand, df_fuel, and df_importance, main features were isolated to answer the side questions.

7.	Preprocessing Pipeline: A Column Transformer was applied with a sklearn pipeline:
•	Numeric features (model_year, hp): Median imputation + StandardScaler
•	Categorical features (brand, fuel_type): Most-frequent imputation + OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore')

8.	Train/Test Split: An 80/20 split was applied using train_test_split with a random_state = 42. All models were evaluated on the same 20% test split.
Key assumptions: We assume that our dataset reflects real‑world vehicle listings and that the listed price is a reasonable representation of market value at the time the data was collected.






Model Selection & Experiments
A.	Linear Regression
•	Config: Default sklearn settings.
•	Rationale: Serves as a linear baseline for comparison, allowing us to determine whether the four main features and price exhibit a sufficiently linear relationship before moving on to more complex random forest and gradient boosting models.
B.	Random Forest Classifier
•	Config: n_estimators = 300, max_features = 'sqrt', random_state = 42, n_jobs = -1.
•	Rationale: Random forest is robust to outliers and capable of capturing nonlinear relationships. n_estimators = 300 helps ensure stable predictions, and max_features = 'sqrt' promotes diversity among trees and helps reduce overfitting. These settings are well suited to our dataset because brand is a complex categorical variable that has a relationship with price.
C.	Gradient Boosting Classifier
•	Config: n_estimators = 400, random_state = 42.
•	Rationale: Gradient boosting builds trees sequentially, allowing errors from previous trees to be corrected. n_estimators = 400 allows the model to capture finer patterns in the data, and random_state = 42 ensures reproducibility. This model serves as a strong comparison point to determine whether sequential error correction outperforms random forest and also acts as a check that our data and preprocessing are on the right track.
•	All models were trained on 80% of the data and evaluated on a held‑out 20% test set







Performance Summary:
Model	R²	MAE	RMSE
Linear Regression	0.6891	$6,076.80	$10,176.45
Random Forest	0.9102	$2,681.89	$5,470.98
Gradient Boosting	0.8772	$3,371.31	$6,394.93

Interpretation:
•	Linear regression performed the worst of all the models, with an R² of about 0.69 and MAE and RMSE values significantly greater than those of random forest and gradient boosting. This confirms that price does not simply follow a linear relationship with the main features (brand, model year, and horsepower) and instead that these variables interact in more complex ways that are not fully captured by a linear model.
•	Random forest greatly outperformed the linear regression baseline, reaching an R² score of about 0.91, an MAE of approximately 2,682 USD, and an RMSE of about 5,471 USD. These results indicate that the nonlinear interactions between brand, model year, and horsepower are very important and that tree‑based ensemble methods capture patterns in this dataset very effectively. An R² of 0.91 means that about 91% of the variation in used car prices is explained using only these four main variables.
•	Gradient boosting also substantially outperformed the linear baseline but was still slightly worse than random forest. This suggests that, for this dataset, random forest’s ensemble strategy works better than gradient boosting’s sequential error‑correction approach.







