•	The Feature importance analysis from the random forest model revealed that horsepower (HP) was the single strongest predictor of price, accounting for 42% of the model’s importance. Model year ranked second at 29%, confirming that newer vehicles are significantly higher in price than older ones. Together, these numeric features account for over 70% of the model’s importance, suggesting that they are the primary drivers of used car pricing.
•	The brand Porsche ranked third at 18%, which stands out because it is the only brand with very substantial weight in the dataset. The remaining brands—Audi, Lexus, Nissan, BMW, and Ford—each contributed less than 1.2% individually, showing that outside of Porsche, brand alone is not a dominant predictor when horsepower and model year are included.
•	Finally, overall fuel type had the least influence, suggesting that fuel type is not a major independent driver of price, although it still contributes a small amount.
Side Question Findings:
