•	Model Year vs Price: a clear upward trend was observed with average prices rising sharply for recent model years, with an extreme jump from vehicles that are from 2018 or newer

•	Brand vs Price: The 10 most expressive brands by average price were dominated by luxury and exotic brands, with the average price several times higher than regular brands.

•	Fuel Type vs Price: Electric and premium-fuel vehicles were higher in price; standard gas vehicles showed the widest price range across the dataset.
Limitations, Ethics, Reflection
Limitations:
1.	Feature Scope: Only four features were used for modeling. Many additional variables in the dataset—such as torque, drivetrain, body type, and reliability rating—were not included and likely account for much of the remaining unexplained variance.
2.	Price type: The dataset reflects listed prices, not final sale or transaction prices. Actual sale prices may differ due to negotiation, dealer markups, or changing market conditions, so it is important to keep these factors in mind when interpreting the results.
3.	Dataset time range: Vehicles from earlier model years (pre‑2010) may be underrepresented, which could introduce bias in the model year predictor toward more recent vehicles.
4.	Web scraped Data: Because this dataset was web scraped, there may be inconsistencies in how different listing sources report features such as fuel type or horsepower.
5.	Generalization: This model was trained on listings from a specific time period and geographic context and should not be expected to generalize reliably to other markets or future pricing conditions. It is better viewed as a tool to provide a general estimate rather than an exact valuation.



Ethical Considerations
Our model weighs brand heavily in price prediction, so it may encode and reinforce existing market biases—for example, confirming that certain manufacturers are “worth more” regardless of actual vehicle quality. If deployed in the real world, this could disadvantage buyers of lower‑cost used vehicles by making some brands appear more expensive or more desirable than they should be. Any real‑world application should include clear transparency about what the model can and cannot account for and should be tested and reviewed by multiple stakeholders before use.
Reflection:
This project shows that a set of four variables can explain over 90% of used car price variation when an appropriate model is applied. One surprising finding was how little importance fuel type had compared with the other three variables; given the rise of EVs and hybrids, we expected fuel type to be a stronger differentiator. If we were to extend this project, we would incorporate more features to account for the remaining variance and further tune our models to achieve even better performance. We would also experiment with larger and more geographically diverse datasets to improve generalization and robustness.
